Most languages handle errors by throwing them. Something goes wrong, an exception flies up the call stack, and somewhere, you hope, a catch block grabs it. Scala can do that too, but it offers something better, and the whole philosophy of error handling in Scala comes down to one shift: treat failure as a value you return, not as control flow you throw.

Let's start with the throwing style, because Scala fully supports it. You wrap risky code in a try block. If it throws, control jumps to the catch, which is just a pattern match on the exception: case e of type IllegalArgumentException, do one thing; case anything else, fall back. And a finally block runs no matter what, success or failure, which is where you put cleanup like closing a file. This works, and sometimes it is the right tool, especially at the boundary with Java code that throws.

But look at what is missing. The signature of a method that throws tells you nothing. A function that can blow up looks identical to one that cannot. The compiler does not track it, callers do not see it coming, and the failure travels invisibly until it crashes or gets caught far away. That invisibility is the problem Scala wants to fix.

The fix is to put the failure into the return type, so it becomes visible, type-checked, and composable. Scala gives you three types for this, each for a different flavor of failure.

The first is Option, for a value that might simply be absent. An Option is either Some, holding a value, or None, holding nothing. So parse, returning Option of Int, says right in its signature: I might give you a number, or I might give you nothing. No nulls, no exceptions, just a value you must acknowledge.

The second is Try, for a computation that might throw. Try of ten divided by zero does not blow up; it catches the exception and hands you back a value: either Success holding the result, or Failure holding the exception. Try is the bridge between the throwing world and the value world. You wrap dangerous code once, and from then on the failure is just data you can pass around.

The third is Either, for when you want the error to carry detail. An Either is Left or Right. By convention Right is the success, and Left is the failure, and crucially the Left can be any type you choose, a message, an error object, a rich description. So check, returning Either of String and Int, gives you back Right of the number when it is positive, or Left of an explanation when it is not. Where Option just says nothing, Either tells you why.

Now the real payoff: because failure is a value, you can compose failures without a single nested if or try. Watch the for-comprehension. You write, for, n drawn from parse of twenty-one, m drawn from parse of two, yield n times m. Each parse returns an Option. The for-comprehension threads them together, and here is the magic: if any step is None, the whole thing short-circuits to None immediately and the later steps never run. If they all succeed, you get Some of forty-two. This is sometimes called railway-oriented programming, your computation rides the success track, and the moment anything fails it switches to the failure track and coasts straight to the end. The same pattern works for Try and for Either, because all three support map and flatMap.

And when you finally need a plain value back, you ask for one safely. r dot getOrElse of zero gives you the number if it is there, or the fallback if it was None. No unwrapping that can crash, no null check, just a total function that always returns something.

So here is the whole mindset. Reach for try and catch only at the edges, mainly when talking to Java. Everywhere else, return failure as a value: Option when something may be absent, Try when something may throw, Either when you want to explain what went wrong. Then compose those values with for-comprehensions and finish with getOrElse. Your error paths become visible in the types, the compiler makes sure you handle them, and your happy path stays clean.
